# Layer Health — Clinical Dashboard

## Architecture

- **Frontend:** React + Tailwind CSS
- **Backend:** Node.js, Express, TypeScript
- **External APIs:**
  - HAPI FHIR (`https://hapi.fhir.org/baseR4`) — patient data (Patient, Condition, Observation)
  - Groq API — AI-generated patient summaries
- **Pattern:** Backend acts as an adapter — fetches raw FHIR, transforms into a clean JSON contract for the frontend via a service chain: `fhirClient → transformer → riskRules → summary`

## Project Structure

```
backend/src/
├── index.ts              # Express entry point
├── routes/patients.ts    # Single endpoint: GET /api/patients/:id/dashboard
├── services/
│   ├── fhirClient.ts     # Only file that talks to HAPI FHIR
│   ├── transformer.ts    # Raw FHIR → clean dashboard types
│   ├── riskRules.ts      # Rule-based risk flagging (sync, no AI)
│   └── summary.ts        # Groq AI summary + rule-based fallback
└── types/
    ├── fhir.ts           # Raw FHIR resource shapes
    └── dashboard.ts      # Clean output types (DashboardResponse, RiskFlag)

frontend/src/
├── App.tsx               # Root — owns state, renders panels
├── components/           # SearchBar, DemographicsPanel, ConditionsList, ObservationsList, AISummaryBox, RiskFlagsSection
├── services/api.ts       # fetchDashboard(id) → calls backend
└── types/dashboard.ts    # Mirrors backend output types
```

## FHIR Boundaries

- **Never invent FHIR field names.** Always verify against the actual HAPI FHIR response or the FHIR R4 spec before accessing nested fields.
- **Always handle missing/malformed FHIR fields.** Use safe access (`?.`) and provide fallback defaults. FHIR resources often have optional or absent fields — never assume a field exists.
- **Do not hard-code FHIR resource structures from memory.** If unsure about a field path (e.g. `name[0].given[0]`), check the FHIR R4 resource definition or test against the live HAPI server first.
- **`fhirClient.ts` is the only file that touches HAPI FHIR.** No other file should import axios or make HTTP calls to the FHIR server.

## Coding Rules

- **Minimum diff only.** When implementing a feature or fixing a bug, make only the minimum code changes required. Never modify unrelated code.
- **Trace integrity.** Before every change, verify that the implementation doesn't break any other part of the service chain (`fhirClient → transformer → riskRules → summary → route`).
- **Type safety end-to-end.** Frontend `dashboard.ts` types must always mirror backend `dashboard.ts` types. If you change one, change the other.
- **No `any` types.** Always use explicit TypeScript interfaces. Raw FHIR data uses `fhir.ts` types; clean output uses `dashboard.ts` types.
- **Fallbacks are mandatory.** Every transformer function must have a safe default (e.g. `name ?? 'Unknown'`, `value ?? 0`). Never let a missing FHIR field crash the app.
- **Summary resilience.** `summary.ts` must always return a string — if Groq fails, the rule-based fallback runs silently. Never throw from the summary service.
- **Risk flags are pure.** `riskRules.ts` is sync, has no external calls, and no side effects. Rules live in config arrays, not if/else chains.
- **Single endpoint.** The backend exposes only `GET /api/patients/:id/dashboard`. Do not add new endpoints without explicit approval.
- **CORS enabled.** Backend must allow cross-origin requests from the frontend dev server.

## Response Contract

The dashboard endpoint always returns this shape:

```json
{
  "patient": { "id", "name", "gender", "birthDate" },
  "conditions": [{ "id", "display", "status", "onsetDate" }],
  "observations": [{ "id", "display", "value", "unit", "effectiveDate" }],
  "summary": "string (always present)",
  "flags": [{ "type", "severity", "message" }]
}
```

- `summary` is always a string — AI-generated or rule-based
- `flags` is always an array — empty `[]` means no risks
- `severity` is one of: `HIGH`, `MEDIUM`, `LOW`
